r\nततः परमा वश्यतेन्द्रियाणाम्॥५५॥\r\n\r\n<b>PYS 2.55: Tatah parama vaśyata indriyaṇam </b>\r\n\r\n<i>this leads to the absolute control of the sense organs</i>\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>•tatah = then, thereby, from that</li>\r\n	<li>•parama = highest, supreme, ultimate, perfected</li>\r\n	<li>•vashyata = mastery, control, being willed</li>\r\n	<li>•indriyanam = of the mental organs of actions and senses</li>\r\n</ul>', 'Pratyāhāra', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '60-revision-v1', '', '', '2013-11-10 21:02:12', '2013-11-10 21:02:12', '', 60, 'http://localhost:8888/wpyogdiksha-nov2013/?p=61', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(62, 1, '2013-11-10 21:03:28', '2013-11-10 21:03:28', '<i>Dhyāna</i> (ध्यान) or meditation is a blissful state of mind where one''s consciousness is absorbed in the essence of the object of contemplation. This state is a result of dedicated practice of the previous (especially involutionary) stages.\r\n<p style="text-align: center;"><img class="aligncenter  wp-image-43" alt="Ashtanga Yoga" src="http://localhost:8888/wpyogdiksha-nov2013/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/2013/11/shapeimage_42.png" width="883" height="512" /></p>\r\nतत्र प्रत्ययैकतानता ध्यानम्॥२॥\r\n\r\n<b>PYS 3.2: Tatra Pratyaya Ekatānatā Dhyānam  </b>\r\n\r\n<i>the union of mind and the object is Dyana; meditation</i>\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>•tatra = there, therein (in that place or desha of 3.1)</li>\r\n	<li>•pratyaya = the cause, the feeling, causal or cognitive principle, notion, content of mind, presented idea, cognition</li>\r\n	<li>•ekatanata = one continuous flow of uninterrupted attention (eka = one; tanata = continued directedness)</li>\r\n	<li>•dhyanam = meditation</li>\r\n</ul>', 'Dhyāna', '', 'publish', 'open', 'closed', '', 'dhyana', '', '', '2013-12-02 16:46:30', '2013-12-02 16:46:30', '', 41, 'http://localhost:8888/wpyogdiksha-nov2013/?page_id=62', 7, 'page', '', 0),
(63, 1, '2013-11-10 21:03:28', '2013-11-10 21:03:28', '<i>Dhyāna</i> (ध्यान) or meditation is a blissful state of mind where one''s consciousness is absorbed in the essence of the object of contemplation. This state is a result of dedicated practice of the previous (especially involutionary) stages.\r\n\r\n<a href="http://localhost:8888/wpyogdiksha-nov2013/wp-content/uploads/2013/11/shapeimage_42.png"><img class="aligncenter size-full wp-image-43" alt="Ashtanga Yoga" src="http://localhost:8888/wpyogdiksha-nov2013/wp-content/uploads/2013/11/shapeimage_42.png" width="883" height="512" /></a>\r\n\r\nतत्र प्रत्ययैकतानता ध्यानम्॥२॥\r\n\r\n<b>PYS 3.2: Tatra Pratyaya Ekatānatā Dhyānam  </b>\r\n\r\n<i>the union of mind and the object is Dyana; meditation</i>\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>•tatra = there, therein (in that place or desha of 3.1)</li>\r\n	<li>•pratyaya = the cause, the feeling, causal or cognitive principle, notion, content of mind, presented idea, cognition</li>\r\n	<li>•ekatanata = one continuous flow of uninterrupted attention (eka = one; tanata = continued directedness)</li>\r\n	<li>•dhyanam = meditation</li>\r\n</ul>', 'Dhyāna', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '62-revision-v1', '', '', '2013-11-10 21:03:28', '2013-11-10 21:03:28', '', 62, 'http://localhost:8888/wpyogdiksha-nov2013/?p=63', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(64, 1, '2013-11-10 21:04:14', '2013-11-10 21:04:14', '<i>Samādhi</i> (समाधि) is the final stage of the path of Yoga. It may be roughly translated as liberation. Through constant practice of meditation, the mind unites with the source of creation.\r\n\r\nThe individual soul (<i>ātman</i>) fuses with the cosmic consciousness (<i>brahman</i>)\r\n<p style="text-align: center;"><img class="aligncenter  wp-image-43" alt="Ashtanga Yoga" src="http://localhost:8888/wpyogdiksha-nov2013/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/2013/11/shapeimage_42.png" width="883" height="512" /></p>\r\nतदेवार्थमात्रनिर्भासं स्वरूपशून्यमिव समाधिः॥३॥\r\n\r\n<b>PYS 3.3: Tadeva Arthamātranirbhāsam Svarūpaśūnyam Iva Samādhih  </b>\r\n\r\n<i>when only the essence of the object shines forth in the mind, as if devoid of it''s own form, </i>\r\n\r\n<i>that state of deep absorption is Samadhi. </i>\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>•tad = that</li>\r\n	<li>•eva = the same</li>\r\n	<li>•artha = object, place, point</li>\r\n	<li>•matra = only, alone</li>\r\n	<li>•nirbhasam = shines forth, appears</li>\r\n	<li>•svarupa = own form, own nature (sva = own; rupe = form, nature)</li>\r\n	<li>•shunyam = devoid of, empty</li>\r\n	<li>•iva = as if, as it were</li>\r\n	<li>•samadhih = meditation in its higher state, deep absorption of meditation, the state of perfected concentration, spiritual absorption</li>\r\n</ul>', 'Samādhi', '', 'publish', 'open', 'closed', '', 'samadhi', '', '', '2013-12-02 16:46:58', '2013-12-02 16:46:58', '', 41, 'http://localhost:8888/wpyogdiksha-nov2013/?page_id=64', 8, 'page', '', 0);
